message.content:
The start symbol S can only expand in one of the following five ways:

1. S → NT54 NT50  (first token must come from NT54)
2. S → NT57 NT51  (first token must come from NT57)
3. S → NT37 NT47  (first token must come from NT37)
4. S → NT71 NT51  (first token must come from NT71)
5. S → NT64 NT36  (first token must come from NT64)

The given string begins with the terminal t56.  
Therefore, whichever of NT54, NT57, NT37, NT71, or NT64 is the left child of S must be able to derive a string whose first terminal is t56.

Check each candidate:

• NT54 is lexical and can only produce t5 or t29.  
• NT57’s lexical options are t23, t32, t37, and t40; its non‑lexical paths begin with NT3 or NT67, whose lexical possibilities are t13, t19, t38, t7, t26, t0, … none of which is t56.  
• NT37 is lexical t3, or starts with NT29 (lexical t31 or t14).  
• NT71 is lexical t44 or t42, or starts with NT12 (lexical t31 or t22).  
• NT64 is lexical t48 or t51, or starts with NT60, NT26, NT43, or NT23; none of these derives t56 as a first token (their lexical possibilities are t49, t25, t32, t46, t21, t40, t33, t12, t0, t2, t37, t44, …).

Consequently, no possible left child of S can produce a string whose first terminal is t56. Hence the grammar cannot generate any sentence beginning with t56 and, in particular, cannot generate the given 25‑token string.

No

To appear at the beginning of the derived string, the first symbol of every sentential form produced from the start‐symbol S must come from the left–most non‑terminal of the first production used.

The grammar gives only five possibilities for S:

1. S → NT54 NT50  
2. S → NT57 NT51  
3. S → NT37 NT47  
4. S → NT71 NT51  
5. S → NT64 NT36  

Among all non‑terminals in the grammar, the only ones that can produce the
terminal t23 are  

 NT50, NT57 and NT6.  

Therefore, for the first word of the sentence to be t23, the left–most
non‑terminal in the first step must be able to reach one of these three.

• In production (1) the left component is NT54, but NT54 has only the
terminal productions NT54 → 't5' and NT54 → 't29'.  
  Hence NT54 can never yield t23.

• In productions (3) and (4) the left components are NT37 and NT71.
Their terminal alternatives are NT37 → 't3', NT71 → 't44' / 't42';
neither can yield t23, and their binary alternatives always place some
other word before anything that could become t23.  
  Thus they cannot start a derivation with t23.

• In production (5) the left component is NT64.
All ways of expanding NT64 begin with NT60, NT26, NT23, or NT43 (or else
immediately give the terminals 't48' or 't51'); none of those symbols
can reach t23 before emitting some other terminal, so NT64 cannot lead
with t23 either.

• That leaves production (2): S → NT57 NT51.
NT57 can indeed produce t23 directly (NT57 → 't23'), so this is the only
rule that can put t23 at the very front of the derived string.

But NT51 has no binary productions at all; it only has five terminal
rules:

 NT51 → 't52' | 't20' | 't36' | 't27' | 't1' .

Consequently, S → NT57 NT51 can yield only a two‑word string whose second
word is one of {t52, t20, t36, t27, t1}.  
It can never generate the remaining 12 words of the target sentence.

Since the only S‑production that can put t23 first cannot supply the rest
of the required words, while all other S‑productions fail to start with
t23, the 13‑word string

t23 t26 t17 t53 t26 t8 t49 t29 t15 t46 t29 t7 t40

is not in the language of the grammar.

No
